b'20/ Truth is a lonely, and unprofitable, business.'
b'19/ Stop sorting people, including yourself, into groups.'
b'18/ Want to escape? Avoid Facebook, Instagram, Snapchat. Avoid venues and media built around group signaling and conspicuous consumption.'
b'17/ Lies need to be repeated to sustain. The truth just is.'
b'16/ From private truths to public lies. From knowledge to outrage. From positive sum to zero sum.'
b'15/ We are moving from a world where it pays to spread facts to one where it pays to spread opinions. From real goods to signaling goods.'
b'14/ Economic logic will drive an information business towards signaling goods. They\xe2\x80\x99re easy to manufacture & share, and pay social rewards.'
b'13/ Campus social action is a signaling good. That\xe2\x80\x99s why universities are more focused on agreeing what to think than teaching how to think.'
b'12/ Editorial outrage is a signaling good. That\xe2\x80\x99s why former news outlets have switched from facts to opinions and outrage.'
b'11/ Social media has degenerated into a deafening cacophony of groups signaling and repeating their shared myths.'
b'10/ Religious myths, secret histories, conspiracy theories, unfalsifiable beliefs, scapegoats...'
b'9/ Every group has a set of shared myths that signal to believers and against outsiders.'
b'8/ Social media makes it easier to signal wealth via conspicuous consumption. Consuming food, travel, clothing on Instagram and Facebook.'
b'7/ The further, the faster, and the more easily something can be shared, the better it is for signaling. Social media fuels signaling.'
b'6/ Signaling goods can be physical - handbags, watches, and fancy cars. They can be virtual - political, religious, and tribal affiliations.'
b'5/ Signaling goods signal status and affiliation to the other monkeys. They have value when produced or consumed conspicuously.'
b'4/ While the business model for distributing facts and truth dies out, the model for distributing opinions and signaling goods is booming.'
b'3/ Newspapers have been exposed as mostly reprinting Reuters and AP. They can\xe2\x80\x99t make a living selling access to facts anymore.'
b'2/ The facts are still there and people can still reach them. But the institutions selling access to facts have lost their business models.'
b'1/ The Internet lowers the returns to distributing facts, while social media increases the returns to distributing signaling goods.'
